</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mukaka>Mukaka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/20/03 2:30 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:</span><hr size=1> Warriors will never get totally screwed. Too many people see them as critical when going up against unslowable mobs in PoP. Besides, Warrior agro is fixed by simply introducing a few more decent proc'ing weapons.<br>
<br>
Increasing healing agro will not hurt all healing classes. In fact it will help them. Doing a 7000 HP complete heal should put you at the top of the hate list... just as much as firing off a 7000 point nuke would. The big big heals have really offset the game/group balance. If you don't want agro for doing a complete heal, use heal of time spells, have several healing classes, everyone loads up on stuns, etc. Instead of having a cleric, you'll need to have druids, ranger, shaman, bards, ... spreading out some of the healing agro. Suddenly more healing classes are group attractive. Clerics no longer have to save every bit of mana for the last second complete heal -- they can actually nuke, stun, or swing their hammer. I play a planar level Cleric as well, I appreciate a different dynamic than buff and heal. These days it is extremely rare that a CH gains agro unless it is early in the fight.<br>
<br>
Wizards are not buffers. I knew that when I signed up as an apprentice Wizard. My familiar is just that... a creature that is familiar to me... not familiar to my group mates. To make a group effect that would make Wizards group utility perception change significantly would cause balancing outcries in the other classes. Anything less than that would be a cheezy lower level bard effect. <p><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
